TY  - JOUR
AU  - Greenwald, Bruce C.
AU  - Glasspiegel, Robert R.
T1  - Adverse Selection in the Market for Slaves: New Orleans, 1830–1860
PY  - 1983
Y1  - 1983/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/1886022
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 98
IS  - 3
SP  - 479
EP  - 499
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper seeks to cast some light on the importance of adverse selection in competitive markets by examining the market for the sale of slaves in pre-Civil War New Orleans. Estimates of the degree of adverse selection in the New Orleans market are obtained by examining the relative prices of slaves from different regions of origin. These estimates indicate that slaves brought to market may on average have been of 20 percent to 40 percent lower quality than the slave population in general, and that good slaves were perhaps three times less likely to be sold than low quality ones.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1886022
ER  - 



